      "SummaryText": "tractor safety\n\n-Pre-startup review\n\n\n\n\n\nIn addition to our industry leading management programs, we have designed state of the art systems and equipment to control, prevent, detect and mitigate potential accidental releases.\n\n\n\nBPEP employs extensive mechanical integrity and preventive maintenance programs to ensure the integrity of process equipment and safety systems.  Our mechanical integrity program uses equipment surveillance and preventive maintenance techniques to identify preventative maintenance opportunities before failure occurs.  This program also specifies the repairs needed to return equipment to acceptable specifications.\n\n\n\nBPEP's employees are trained to safely perform their assigned tasks.  Our training program includes initial training as well as periodic refresher training and training updates when major process or equipment changes are made.  As part of our training, we include provisions for ensuring that employees understand the training, including written tests and field demonstrations.\n\n\n\nThe processes at BPEP have hazards that must be managed to ensure continued safe operation. The Accident Prevention Program summarized previously is applied to all covered processes at the facility.  Collectively, these prevention program activities prevent potential accident scenarios that could be caused by (1) equipment failures and (2) human errors.\n\n\n\nIn addition to the Accident Prevention Program activities, BPEP utilizes safety features in and around the process operating units to aid in, (1) quickly detecting a release, (2) containing/controlling a release, and (3) reducing the consequences of (mitigating) a release.  The following types of safety features are utilized in various processes:\n\n\n\nRelease Detection\n\n\n\n     - Process area detectors with alarms\n\n     - CTTV surveillance cameras\n\n\n\nRelease Containment/Control\n\n\n\n     - Process pressure relief valves that discharge to a flare 